# 1. position: static üóø

Default value. Elements render in order, as they appear in the document flow.

`top`, `bottom`, `left`, and `right` properties represent **no effect**.

```css
div.static {
  position: static;
  border: 3px solid #73AD21;
}
```

# 2. position: relative üëª

Positioned relative to its normal position.

Setting `top: 20px` adds 20px to the element's top position, forcing it down.

```css
div.relative {
  position: relative;
  left: 30px;
  border: 3px solid #73AD21;
}
```

> üí° **Key Use:** A `relative` parent is often used as a container for `absolute` children!

# 3. position: absolute üìå

Positioned relative to the nearest **positioned** ancestor (instead of positioned relative to the viewport, like fixed).

If no positioned ancestor exists, it uses the document body.

**REMOVED from the normal document flow!**

```css
div.relative {
  position: relative;
  width: 400px;
  height: 200px;
}

div.absolute {
  position: absolute;
  top: 80px;
  right: 0;
}
```

# 4. position: fixed ‚öì

Positioned relative to the **viewport** (browser window).

It stays in the same place even when the page is scrolled (like a navbar or 'back to top' button).

```css
div.fixed {
  position: fixed;
  bottom: 0;
  right: 0;
  width: 300px;
}
```

# 5. position: sticky üçØ

Toggles between `relative` and `fixed` depending on the scroll position.

It behaves like `relative` until it crosses a specified threshold (e.g., `top: 0`), then it becomes `fixed`.

```css
div.sticky {
  position: -webkit-sticky; /* Safari */
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  background-color: green;
  padding: 50px;
}
```

Great for headers that stick to the top as you scroll!

# Z-Index (Layers) üç∞

When elements overlap, `z-index` specifies the stack order.

- Elements with a higher index appear in front of those with a lower index.
- Only works on positioned elements (position: absolute, relative, fixed, or sticky).

```css
img {
  position: absolute;
  left: 0px;
  top: 0px;
  z-index: -1;
}
```

(Negative z-index puts it behind others.)
